WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.550 --> 00:00:03.680
FEMALE SPEAKER: Hi everyone.

00:00:03.680 --> 00:00:05.330
Thanks so much for
coming today.

00:00:05.330 --> 00:00:08.380
I'm very pleased to welcome
Time Wise to Google today.

00:00:08.380 --> 00:00:12.240
Tim is an American anti-racism
activist and writer.

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:14.910
He's the author of six books,
including the highly acclaimed

00:00:14.910 --> 00:00:17.850
memoir "White Like Me,
Reflections on Race from a

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:21.530
Privileged Son." His next book
"The Culture of Cruelty, How

00:00:21.530 --> 00:00:24.670
America's Elite Demonize the
Poor, Valorize the Rich and

00:00:24.670 --> 00:00:28.480
Jeopardize the Future," will
be released in winter 2014.

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:30.650
Please join me in welcoming
him to talk to us today.

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:37.740
TIM WISE: Thank you very
much for coming.

00:00:37.740 --> 00:00:39.690
I'm particularly grateful
that you're here.

00:00:39.690 --> 00:00:43.960
Because even though I've done
this for a very long time, and

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:48.540
now about 24 years of doing
anti-racism work of some sort

00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:52.260
or civil rights work of some
sort and about 18 of those on

00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:54.610
the road speaking to folks
around the country.

00:00:54.610 --> 00:00:57.520
You never really know when
somebody asks you to come in

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:00.300
and talk-- whether it's at a
company or whether it's at a

00:01:00.300 --> 00:01:02.680
college or a high school or
occasionally a middle school

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:04.840
or community group, wherever
it is I go--

00:01:04.840 --> 00:01:05.880
who's going to show up.

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:07.310
How many people are
going to show up.

00:01:07.310 --> 00:01:09.080
How much interest there is
in the conversation.

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:11.940
One of the reasons in particular
you don't know that

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:15.720
nowadays, maybe even more so
than when I began this work so

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:19.880
long ago, is that in just about
every sense, all the

00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:22.390
other voices in the culture-- at
least the majority of them,

00:01:22.390 --> 00:01:23.280
if not all--

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:26.850
seem to be telling you in a
lot of different ways that

00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:28.930
this kind of conversation
really isn't necessary.

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:31.170
That we really don't have
to have this talk.

00:01:31.170 --> 00:01:33.550
That we don't have to address
issues of race or racial

00:01:33.550 --> 00:01:36.600
equity in the workplace or in
the school system or the

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:39.530
justice system or the housing
market or anywhere else.

00:01:39.530 --> 00:01:42.370
Because to hear those voices
tell it-- and again, you'll

00:01:42.370 --> 00:01:44.140
hear this echoed through
the media.

00:01:44.140 --> 00:01:47.830
You'll hear this echoed
through the words of

00:01:47.830 --> 00:01:51.170
politicians and talking heads
all around the country.

00:01:51.170 --> 00:01:53.700
We're living in this--
presumably, in their mind--

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:56.280
sort of post-racial era where
these conversations, though

00:01:56.280 --> 00:01:59.720
they were very, very important
a while back, they're now,

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:02.740
like, so 1965 or something.

00:02:02.740 --> 00:02:06.190
Or maybe even 1995, if
we're being generous.

00:02:06.190 --> 00:02:09.610
Or maybe even 2007, if we're
being really generous, right?

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:12.290
But now that we're in this
post-racial era symbolized, of

00:02:12.290 --> 00:02:15.200
course, first and foremost by
the election not once but

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:17.847
twice of a man of color as
president, you don't have to

00:02:17.847 --> 00:02:18.700
have this conversation.

00:02:18.700 --> 00:02:19.890
I don't need to give it.

00:02:19.890 --> 00:02:20.770
You don't need to hear it.

00:02:20.770 --> 00:02:23.355
In fact, I remember immediately
after President

00:02:23.355 --> 00:02:26.043
Obama was elected the first
time, I opened my email the

00:02:26.043 --> 00:02:28.740
next day and knew there would
be all kinds of wonderful,

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:31.910
lovely things that people
would have to say to me.

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:35.040
And one of them was especially
pertinent to this

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:35.680
conversation.

00:02:35.680 --> 00:02:37.510
It was all capital letters.

00:02:37.510 --> 00:02:39.700
So you know you're dealing
with crazy when it's all

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:42.750
capital letters and they're
e-screaming at you, as if I

00:02:42.750 --> 00:02:44.820
wouldn't have known they were
pissed if they had taken the

00:02:44.820 --> 00:02:46.050
caps lock off.

00:02:46.050 --> 00:02:49.130
And the email was something to
the effect of saying, well

00:02:49.130 --> 00:02:51.810
now, you're going to have to
find a new hustle, right?

00:02:51.810 --> 00:02:55.340
Because that's clearly what
fighting racism is, is just a

00:02:55.340 --> 00:02:58.010
big hustle to make a lot of
money and get very famous.

00:02:58.010 --> 00:03:00.510
Because that is exactly what
you would do if you were

00:03:00.510 --> 00:03:02.740
sitting in a dorm room at the
age of 19 thinking to

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:04.860
yourself, what the hell would I
do if I wanted to get really

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:05.860
rich and really famous?

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:07.530
Oh, I would fight
white supremacy.

00:03:07.530 --> 00:03:09.030
Because that always
works out well.

00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:12.090
So anyway, it said, you should
get a new hustle.

00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:14.770
Because now that Barack Obama
has been elected, clearly we

00:03:14.770 --> 00:03:17.040
don't have to have this
conversation anymore.

00:03:17.040 --> 00:03:18.010
Racism is dead.

00:03:18.010 --> 00:03:21.320
And you're going to have to find
some other line of work.

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:23.710
Now, if that were only one
voice and an angry email

00:03:23.710 --> 00:03:26.700
saying that and the day after
an election, then maybe I

00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:28.560
wouldn't have taken it very
seriously, just like I don't

00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:31.750
take most of the emails that I
receive all that seriously.

00:03:31.750 --> 00:03:34.970
But unfortunately, that mantra
was repeated, usually in a lot

00:03:34.970 --> 00:03:37.980
more erudite way than that.

00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:38.870
Without the capital letters.

00:03:38.870 --> 00:03:40.690
Without the electronic
or real screaming.

00:03:40.690 --> 00:03:43.380
But by people oftentimes very
well intended and quite

00:03:43.380 --> 00:03:46.410
sincere in their belief that
we're living in this sort of

00:03:46.410 --> 00:03:48.790
post-racial era where this
conversation is not important.

00:03:48.790 --> 00:03:51.700
Of course, if we just think
about it for maybe two

00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:54.540
seconds, we can recognize, I
hope, almost immediately why

00:03:54.540 --> 00:03:57.590
the notion of post-raciality
is absurd.

00:03:57.590 --> 00:03:59.740
At least if the only evidence
you have for it is the

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:01.520
election of a black
man as President

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:02.220
of the United States.

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:04.050
If you have other evidence,
feel free to present it.

00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:07.090
But if that's the sum total of
your evidence-- if that's

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:10.660
exhibit one and two and three
through seven, then you're

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:12.020
probably not a very
firm ground.

00:04:12.020 --> 00:04:14.470
Anymore so than we would have
been on firm ground if someone

00:04:14.470 --> 00:04:18.490
were to have said, let's say, in
Pakistan in 1989, the year

00:04:18.490 --> 00:04:22.300
after Benazir Bhutto, a woman,
was first elected president of

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:23.800
that country, that
sexism was no

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:25.620
longer an issue in Pakistan.

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:27.220
Patriarchy has been smashed.

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:28.750
And this we know, because
a woman is the

00:04:28.750 --> 00:04:30.350
head of state in Pakistan.

00:04:30.350 --> 00:04:33.290
Or when Margaret Thatcher was
elected in Great Britain.

00:04:33.290 --> 00:04:37.670
Or when Indira Gandhi was
elected in India.

00:04:37.670 --> 00:04:39.790
Or Golda Meir in Israel.

00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:42.340
Or Corazon Aquino in
the Philippines.

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:44.180
So in all of these countries--
you can probably think of

00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:45.930
others-- there have been
female heads of state.

00:04:45.930 --> 00:04:46.910
We still haven't had one.

00:04:46.910 --> 00:04:49.100
So if I were to suggest, for
instance, to my two daughters,

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:51.940
who are 12 and 10, that what
they probably really ought to

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:54.560
do if they want equal
opportunity as women is pack

00:04:54.560 --> 00:04:58.170
up their bags and move to
Karachi, my guess is that even

00:04:58.170 --> 00:05:00.970
the 10-year-old, who has no idea
where the hell Karachi

00:05:00.970 --> 00:05:04.340
is, would know that the odds
were that wasn't a good bet.

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:06.670
Just because a woman had been
the head of state in Pakistan

00:05:06.670 --> 00:05:09.625
did not mean that other women
were going to, therefore, have

00:05:09.625 --> 00:05:10.350
equal opportunity.

00:05:10.350 --> 00:05:12.530
So we wouldn't make the argument
about sexism in those

00:05:12.530 --> 00:05:15.030
countries just because they've
had female heads of state.

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:17.690
And I would hope that we would
be able to see through the

00:05:17.690 --> 00:05:20.070
argument about race as it
relates to this country.

00:05:20.070 --> 00:05:22.810
But it's very easy to get sucked
into that rhetoric of

00:05:22.810 --> 00:05:23.890
post-raciality.

00:05:23.890 --> 00:05:27.180
And I think maybe it's more than
ever possible in a place

00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:29.900
like Silicon Valley, where more
so than just about any

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:33.010
other sort of industrial
area of America, both

00:05:33.010 --> 00:05:35.570
geographically and historically,
there is this

00:05:35.570 --> 00:05:40.290
very widely accepted mythology
that this, more so than any

00:05:40.290 --> 00:05:43.330
other part of the American
economy and any other part of

00:05:43.330 --> 00:05:46.680
the geography of the country,
is this pure meritocracy.

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:48.010
All those other industries,
no.

00:05:48.010 --> 00:05:50.080
They're not really
meritocratic.

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:51.850
We know that there are
networks and there's

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:54.980
clubbiness and there's cultures
that get sort of

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:59.710
reestablished and resurrected
and passed on, but not here.

00:05:59.710 --> 00:06:03.930
There's no such thing as
clubbiness or insider

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:07.800
advantages or networks, or even
a criteria that might

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:09.250
itself not be all that

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:10.700
meritocratic in Silicon Valley.

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:12.960
Well, the smirks on some your
faces at least suggest to me

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:15.870
that you've thought through this
a minute and realize that

00:06:15.870 --> 00:06:20.360
some of that rhetoric
is quite well sold

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:22.830
but quite a bit overblown.

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:25.570
Because ultimately, at the end
of the day, we do have to ask

00:06:25.570 --> 00:06:27.570
ourselves one very
simple question.

00:06:27.570 --> 00:06:30.870
When people tell us that this
industry or that industry or

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:33.320
that this country or the
overall economy or this

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:35.710
particular company is
meritocratic, it then begs the

00:06:35.710 --> 00:06:36.480
question, right?

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:40.900
That if in fact this company
and the larger part of the

00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:44.310
economy that it represents and
of which it is a part is truly

00:06:44.310 --> 00:06:46.810
meritocratic, then you would
have to really ask yourself

00:06:46.810 --> 00:06:49.690
some hard questions about what
that means in terms of who

00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:52.490
possesses merit in this country
and who doesn't.

00:06:52.490 --> 00:06:56.550
Because if you have an entire
area, both of the economy and

00:06:56.550 --> 00:06:59.510
a geographic region, this being
the Silicon Valley where

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:03.850
only about 6% of all the
employees in the various firms

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:06.690
and companies here are black and
Latino, and you believe at

00:07:06.690 --> 00:07:10.590
the same time that this is a
pure meritocracy as a part of

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:12.870
the economy, then you would have
to actually come to some

00:07:12.870 --> 00:07:15.990
very racist conclusions almost
by definition, right?

00:07:15.990 --> 00:07:19.040
You would have to conclude
that only 6% of the best

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:22.200
people are represented by
African American and Latino

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:25.340
folk who collectively, in
the country, represent

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:30.090
approximately 30% of the
population and in this state,

00:07:30.090 --> 00:07:31.280
quite a bit more than that.

00:07:31.280 --> 00:07:33.240
You would have to assume
that there was this

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:34.570
real dearth of ability.

00:07:34.570 --> 00:07:36.280
This real dearth of merit.

00:07:36.280 --> 00:07:39.790
This real dearth of interest in
having jobs in the growing

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:40.710
part of the economy.

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:43.950
As if somehow black and brown
folks would prefer to stay in

00:07:43.950 --> 00:07:46.800
embedded in parts of the economy
that are rapidly dying

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:49.390
and leave all the really great
jobs disproportionately to

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:51.540
those who were white and of
course, on a gender level and

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:52.600
sex level, those
who were male.

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:55.180
You would also have to assume
some very sexist things.

00:07:55.180 --> 00:07:57.880
If you really buy into the
notion of Silicon Valley as a

00:07:57.880 --> 00:08:00.320
pure meritocracy, you would have
to assume that men are

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:02.380
just that much damn smarter.

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:05.380
And just that much better at
doing certain types of jobs.

00:08:05.380 --> 00:08:07.170
Now, there may or may not
be evidence for that.

00:08:07.170 --> 00:08:08.180
And you may believe there is.

00:08:08.180 --> 00:08:10.220
But certainly not to the
extent we see the

00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:13.450
disproportionalities in not
only this sector of the

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:15.790
economy, but in old sectors
of the economy like

00:08:15.790 --> 00:08:18.060
manufacturing, where the same
kind of thing was true.

00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:22.260
Is it really true that women
were only 1%, 1 and 1/2%, 2%

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:25.000
of the people qualified for jobs
in the old quote unquote

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.100
economy in certain companies,
firms, or industries.

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:29.140
Well, probably not.

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:31.970
But if you're going to accept
that premise, understand where

00:08:31.970 --> 00:08:33.870
it leads you as we try to have
these conversations.

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:36.850
If you're going to assume that
Silicon Valley or that Google

00:08:36.850 --> 00:08:39.630
itself as an entity is a pure
meritocracy, you would have to

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:41.860
assume not only some very racist
and sexist things about

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:44.480
certain folks, which would then,
it seems to me, have an

00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:46.940
impact on how you perceive even
your co-workers who are

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:48.920
women or who are people
of color, right?

00:08:48.920 --> 00:08:51.360
Because if I actually look at
people and think they're part

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:54.290
of a culture or group of people
that are in general not

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:57.090
as good, that are in general
not as qualified, how do I

00:08:57.090 --> 00:08:59.830
really relate to the one or two
that I actually work with?

00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:01.970
Or the five or six that I
see on a regular basis?

00:09:01.970 --> 00:09:04.340
How do I subdivide my
brain into the part

00:09:04.340 --> 00:09:05.250
that says, oh, no.

00:09:05.250 --> 00:09:07.210
This person's just as good
as anybody else.

00:09:07.210 --> 00:09:09.600
But the group they're from
is really screwed up.

00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:11.360
Is that actually something
the human brain

00:09:11.360 --> 00:09:12.320
is capable of doing?

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:14.760
Saying on the one hand that
I believe this group to be

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:17.110
superior to this group, this
group to be harder working,

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:19.620
this group to be more
innovative, this group to be

00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:21.670
better for this particular kind
of job, but there are a

00:09:21.670 --> 00:09:24.080
handful of y'all that are OK and
I'll be able to keep that

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:26.380
in mind as I work with
you on a daily basis.

00:09:26.380 --> 00:09:28.550
And the psychological research
says that's not likely.

00:09:28.550 --> 00:09:31.510
So in fact, if we buy into the
stereotypes, we're likely to

00:09:31.510 --> 00:09:34.440
perpetuate the very culture
that maintains those

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:37.420
inequalities, even if we don't
necessarily intend to do it.

00:09:37.420 --> 00:09:39.440
So how would we know if
we were a meritocracy?

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:42.930
How would we know if racism were
operating in a company or

00:09:42.930 --> 00:09:43.610
in an industry?

00:09:43.610 --> 00:09:45.390
How would we know
if sexism were?

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:48.480
Well, those seem like obvious
questions, but they don't

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:49.710
really have obvious answers.

00:09:49.710 --> 00:09:51.710
Because when you ask them, how
would you know if racism was

00:09:51.710 --> 00:09:53.720
operating, you ask a hundred
people that, you're going to

00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:54.970
have a lot of different
answers.

00:09:54.970 --> 00:09:57.730
One thing we know from history
is that if you're really

00:09:57.730 --> 00:10:00.100
wanting to figure out if racism
is operating, the first

00:10:00.100 --> 00:10:02.720
thing you don't want to do-- as
a general rule, with some

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:05.190
exceptions-- is ask
white people.

00:10:05.190 --> 00:10:06.290
Just being perfectly honest.

00:10:06.290 --> 00:10:08.470
Just like if you want to know
if sexism is operating, you

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:10.850
wouldn't start by asking men.

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:11.750
Just wouldn't make sense.

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:15.130
If you wanted to know if an
industry or a company were

00:10:15.130 --> 00:10:17.690
discriminatory toward those
with disabilities, right?

00:10:17.690 --> 00:10:20.220
On the basis of ablism, you
wouldn't ask the able-bodied.

00:10:20.220 --> 00:10:22.850
Because when you're a member of
a dominant group, whatever

00:10:22.850 --> 00:10:26.310
that is-- whether it's race,
gender, sex, class, sexuality,

00:10:26.310 --> 00:10:29.280
religion, educational
background, or

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:30.900
whatever it might be--

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:32.990
those individuals who are
members of dominant groups--

00:10:32.990 --> 00:10:35.440
and we're all, in just about
every case, members of at

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:36.250
least one or two.

00:10:36.250 --> 00:10:39.350
Everyone I see in this room
has probably got a mix of

00:10:39.350 --> 00:10:39.830
identities.

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:41.790
Some of which make you a
dominant group in certain

00:10:41.790 --> 00:10:42.400
categories.

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:44.640
Others of which make you a
subordinate or potentially

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:46.680
targeted group for
mistreatment and

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:47.830
discrimination on the other.

00:10:47.830 --> 00:10:51.230
When you're dominant, why would
you be expected to know

00:10:51.230 --> 00:10:53.580
